{"key":"processedPost-13696940","value":{"id":13696940,"first":13684454,"last":13720036,"when":1293580027,"utime":"12/29/10 01:47 AM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>runMD said:</strong><br /><blockquote>Quote:<br />Fungi lack chlorophyll and are therefore incapable of photosynthesis. </blockquote></blockquote><br />This is one of the biggest factors which confuse new growers.&nbsp; Photosynthesis is a term which applies to plants.&nbsp; Fungi are not plants.&nbsp; For one to infer that since fungi appear to not use the process of photosynthesis, that they do not derive energy from light is jumping to an unsupportable conclusion.&nbsp; It's similar to saying that since an electric motor does not burn gasoline, it's incapable of producing energy to turn the wheels on a car.<br />I've been trying to make the case for a long time that fungi are more closely related to humans than plants,&nbsp; incidentally while <a href=\"/forums/showflat.php/Number/11115617#11115617\" class=\"pp\" target=\"_blank\">making this same point</a> about the importance of lighting.&nbsp; There's a reason mushrooms turn towards the light, exposing as much of their cap surface as possible to the rays."}}